{{Infobox artist | bgcolour = | name = Gustave Boulanger | image = Boulanger2.jpg|185px | imagesize = 160px | caption = | birth_name = Gustave Clarence Rodolphe Boulanger | birth_date = 25 April 1824 | birth_place = [[Paris]], [[France]] | death_date = October 1888 | death_place = Paris | nationality = French | field = | training = Pierre-Jules Jollivet; [[Hippolyte Delaroche|Delaroche]]; École de Rome | movement = Academic art, Orientalist themes | works = | patrons = | influenced by = | influenced = | awards = 25 April 1824 }} '''Gustave Clarence Rodolphe Boulanger''' (25 April 1824 – October 1888) was a French [[figure painting|figure painter]] known for his classical and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]] subjects.
==Life and career== [[File:Boulanger harem-du-palais.jpg|thumb|275px|''The Harem'']] Boulanger was born at Paris in 1824. He was orphaned at age 14, and his uncle and guardian subsequently sent him to the studio of Pierre-Jules Jollivet and then to [[Hippolyte Delaroche|Delaroche]] in 1840. In 1849 took the [[Prix de Rome]] with his painting, ''Ulysses'', a work which combined a classical approach with Orientalist overtones.<ref name="NIE">{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Boulanger, Gustave |encyclopedia =New International Encyclopaedia |volume =3 |pages=861–62 |publisher=Dodd, Mead and Company |year=1906 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HjkrAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA362&dq=Boulanger+%22slave+market%22&hl=en&ei=37YVTqH3G4XUgQfE7OX8Dw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Boulanger%20%22slave%20market%22&f=false |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref>
In 1845, he first visited Algeria and this gave him an interest in Orientalist themes, which was taken up later by his friend [[Jean-Léon Gérome]]. Boulanger's knowledge of Pompeii, which he visited while studying at the École de Rome, also gave him ideas for many future pictures. His paintings are prime examples of [[academic art]] of the time, particularly [[history painting]]. Boulanger had visited Italy, Greece, and North Africa, and his paintings reflect his attention to culturally correct details and skill in rendering the female form.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Masler |first=Marilyn |authorlink= |editor-last=Masler |editor-first=Marilyn |editor2-last=Pacini |editor2-first=Marina |contribution=Embracing the Academic Tradition |title =Carl Gutherz: Poetic Vision and Academic Ideals |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |year=2009 |location=Jackson, Tennessee |pages =38–39 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RCz8zO0_ItgC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |isbn=978-0-915525-11-9}}</ref> His works include a ''Moorish Cafe'' (1848), ''Cæsar at the Rubicon'' (1865), the ''Promenade in the Street of Tombs, Pompeii'' (1869), and ''[[The Slave Market (Boulanger painting)|The Slave Market]]'' (1888). The recipient of many medals, he became a member of the [[Institut de France]] in 1882.<ref name="NIE"/>
He began teaching at the [[Institut de France]] in 1882 and was an influential teacher, noted for his dislike of the [[Impressionism]].
==Pupils== Boulanger taught at [[Académie Julian]],<ref>(fr) [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k97374353/f100.item.r=%22Acad%C3%A9mie%20Julian%22.zoom Gallica . French archives]</ref> among his students were : {{dynamic list}} {{div col|colwidth=30em}} * [[Jules Benoit-Lévy]] * [[Walter Lofthouse Dean]] * [[Arthur Wesley Dow]] <ref>Waller, S. (ed.), ''Foreign Artists and Communities in Modern Paris, 1870-1914: Strangers in Paradise,'' Routledge, 2017, p. 119</ref> * [[Ernst Friedrich von Liphart]]<ref>[https://archive.is/20131230232257/http://www.rusartnet.com/biographies/russian-artists/19th-century/late-19th-century/baron-ernst-friedrich-von-liphart Ernst Friedrich von Liphart], RusArtnet, retrieved 1 January 2014</ref> * [[Théophile Poilpot]] * [[Osman Hamdi Bey]] * [[Alexander Ignatius Roche]],<ref>http://www.caltongallery.co.uk/Artist.aspx?id=Artist.ROCHE</ref> one of the [[Glasgow Boys]] * [[Georges Rochegrosse]] <ref>Waller, S. (ed.), ''Foreign Artists and Communities in Modern Paris, 1870-1914: Strangers in Paradise,'' Routledge, 2017, p. 119</ref> * [[Elmer Boyd Smith]]<ref>{{cite web |title=biography of Elmer Boyd SMITH (1860-1943) |url=https://www.artprice.com/artist/26878/elmer-boyd-smith/biography |website=artprice |accessdate=Oct 7, 2018}}</ref> * [[Albert Beck Wenzell]],<ref>http://americanartgallery.org/artist/readmore/id/609</ref> {{div col end}}
